Realized that I was being dumb in my desire to not have to repeat myself at all.  It's much simpler to just use a separate main_frame layout for each theme, even though there's a lot of repetition that way.  The code is much cleaner, it's much easier to modify and understand each theme, and the only real downside is that when you add or remove items from the layout, you have to do it from each layout separately -- but you probably won't do that all that often.

Run Service in foreground to avoid being killed unless truly necessary.  Since it will always be restarted soon anyway, it's lightweight, and it's already notifying, so the user expects it to be running, it's not the ideal candidate for killing.  Perhaps most significantly, this supposedly also keeps task killers on modern Android from killing it.

Bugfix: The full widget would sometimes become defunct under low-memory conditions.  This was due to the Service being killed and not properly retrieving the list of widget ids from the system.  It turns out that the list of existing widget ids must be requested independently for each AppWidgetProvider class.  I now do this on every update, although I could (and perhaps should, for performance reasons) go back to only doing it in onCreate() and syncing with every widget addition or removal now that I understand how it works.  Committing working code for now.

Go back to technique of keeping track of widget ids as they're added and removed, but properly retrieve them from the system in onCreate(), rather than retrieving on every update.  This should be more lightweight.
